June 8th<hr>Sean Smallman said on Wed Mar 6 2002 <br>Hey Steve,<br>
<br>
I'm sorry that it took a few days to reply to you.  Contrary to what some claim, we don't check DeckTech out all the time.  We do make an effort to check it out on a weekly basis at least, to keep up with our playing community here.  We do try to listen to you guys, even though we don't always answer you.<br>
<br>
Considering what happened over the last year (slowly losing the battle to keep SWCCG lisence, Sept.11/DecipherCon cancellation, and a tough economy for all game companies), we try to keep our comments positive.  Thanks for your reply, Steve.<br>
<br>
During the license negotiations that lasted into late 2001 and even now that the end of them has come, we have not been permitted to comment much about them.  Nor would we, as almost every company would choose to not comment on negotiations even when allowed.  You won't find the answers you seek, as to why this and that happened regarding the SW license.  We gave it our best effort to keep it, and we lost.  We are doing whatever it takes (within our abilities) to reward our customers for their loyalties over the years, and I hope that you will see and appreciate that.<hr>Steve Marshall said on Sat Mar 9 2002 <br>Sean: Thanks for the reply. My final question to you is this: Why put out 5 sets in a huge, non-playtested rush after such a long break between Endor and DS2, then DS2 and Tatooine? (Ref2 only had 54 NEW cards, and most of those were combos, so it doesn't really count.) This is the disrespect that really gets to me. I know that you couldn't / wouldn't talk about the license, and I understand that from a business point of view. But to drag out sets, each one WAY more powerful than the last (and necessary to be competitive, since nobody says that the game is ending as of that time). If Decipher still wants to be one of my good guys, that's the last question they need to answer. I look forward to your reply.